 that nurtures rather than depletes it. She deftly illustrates the processes by which Indigenous people have been asserting control over the Northwest Coast art industry by reshaping it to reflect local models of property, relationships, and economics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommercial artxSocial aspectszNorthwest Coast of North America. 0aCommodificationzNorthwest Coast of North America. 0aIndian artxEconomic aspectszNorthwest Coast of North America. 0aIndian artistszNorthwest Coast of North AmericaxEconomic conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311141792940uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483740840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774837408423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774837408/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-141792-9  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles